# Security Baseline

## 1. No data at rest — the prime directive
Never persist consumer PII or credit data to any database or disk (ADR-0001). Uploaded report bytes are encrypted in memory (AES-256-GCM via `cypher.py`), parsed from streams, then dropped. Temp files, "just cache it", and retention features are all violations.

## 2. Input validation
Validate all inputs at the boundary — explicit checks/schemas in Flask routes, Zod in the frontend. Reject invalid input with 422 (the consent gate already does; keep that pattern).

## 3. Error responses
Sanitize error responses. Never return stack traces, internal paths, or parsed report content to clients.

## 4. Logging & admin surfaces
Never log names, emails, phone numbers, or report content. The admin dashboard shows non-PII only (initials, truncated session id, status, counts) — keep it that way.

## 5. Secrets
Env vars only (`SECRET_KEY`, `CYPHER_SERVER_SECRET`, `ADMIN_KEY`, `STRIPE_*`, `CLICK2MAIL_*`). The repo carries `.env.example` without values. `ADMIN_KEY` must fail closed — no documented defaults, ever.

## 6. Payments
Stripe webhook signatures must be verified (`STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET`). Manual-pay paths require the consent flag and admin release; never auto-unlock letters.

## 7. Sessions
Session state is in-memory and keyed per session with derived Fernet keys — never widen to shared state, never add a second gunicorn worker, never move session ids into URLs.

## 8. CORS
Explicit origins only (the Vercel frontend + local dev). Never `*` in production.
